<a class="definition-word" data-category="general-biology" id="antibody">Antibody</a> - Also known as an immunoglobulin (Ig), is a large, Y-shaped protein produced mainly by plasma cells that is used by the immune system to identify and neutralise pathogens such as <a href="#bacteria">bacteria</a> and <a href="#virus">viruses</a>.
                    <!-- VERIFY --> The average size of an antibody is about 10 nm in length <span class="citation">(Reth 2013: Nature Immunology - Matching cellular dimensions with molecular sizes)</span> and its molecular weight would be about 150 kDa <span class="citation">(Padlan EA. Anatomy of the antibody molecule. Mol. Immunol. 1994;31:169-217)</span>.